04308nam a22006015i 9780226428772DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264287727 a10.7208/97802264287722doi  a(DE-B1597)524518  a(OCoLC)969646415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aBIO0000002bisacsh1 aEngel, Amir, eauthor.10aGershom Scholem :bAn Intellectual Biography /cAmir Engel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German-Jewish Cultural History and Literature, Franz Rosenzweig Minerva Research Center, Hebrew University of Jerusalem00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. The Stories of Gershom Scholem -- tChapter 2. Writing the Myth of Exile: In Search of Political Rejuvenation, 1913-1918 -- tChapter 3. Messianism as Symbol: The Lurianic School and the Emergence of a Mystical-Political Society -- tChapter 4. When a Dream Comes True: Zionist Politics in Palestine, 1923-1931 -- tChapter 5. Against All Odds: Sabbatean Belief and the Sabbatean Movement -- tChapter 6. For the Love of Israel: The Turn from the Fringe to the Mainstream of Zionist Thinking -- tChapter 7. The Man and the Image -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGershom Scholem (1897-1982) was ostensibly a scholar of Jewish mysticism, yet he occupies a powerful role in today's intellectual imagination, having an influential contact with an extraordinary cast of thinkers, including Hans Jonas, Martin Buber, Walter Benjamin, Hannah Arendt, and Theodor Adorno. In this first biography of Scholem, Amir Engel shows how Scholem grew from a scholar of an esoteric discipline to a thinker wrestling with problems that reach to the very foundations of the modern human experience.             As Engel shows, in his search for the truth of Jewish mysticism Scholem molded the vast literature of Jewish mystical lore into a rich assortment of stories that unveiled new truths about the modern condition. Positioning Scholem's work and life within early twentieth-century Germany, Palestine, and later the state of Israel, Engel intertwines Scholem's biography with his historiographical work, which stretches back to the Spanish expulsion of Jews in 1492, through the lives of Rabbi Isaac Luria and Sabbatai Zevi, and up to Hasidism and the dawn of the Zionist movement. Through parallel narratives, Engel touches on a wide array of important topics including immigration, exile, Zionism, World War One, and the creation of the state of Israel, ultimately telling the story of the realizations-and failures-of a dream for a modern Jewish existence.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aJewish scholarszGermanyvBiography. 0aJewish scholarszIsraelvBiography. 0aMysticismxJudaism. 0aZionismxHistoryy20th century. 4aExile. 4aGerman Jewish culture. 4aGershom Scholem. 4aHistoriography. 4aHomecoming. 4aJewish mysticism. 4aMyth. 4aZionism. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226428772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226428772.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles